Is there a way to get selected string into a variable or create a new variable in VSCode similar to native variable ${file} which is the current opened file as described here: https://code.visualstudio.com/docs/editor/tasks ?
This variable could be very useful not only for online help for example:

using the native variable ${file} as argument:
{
"version": "0.1.0",
"command": "explorer",
"windows": {
"command": "explorer.exe"
},
"args": ["${file}"]
}

using a suggested variable "${WordSelection}" as argument:
{
"version": "0.1.0",
"command": "explorer",
"windows": {
"command": "explorer.exe"
},
"args": [„https://www.google.cz/search?q=${WordSelection}+site:msdn.microsoft.com"]
}

Thank you!

Create an extension that contributes a command to the commandPallette and uses `resourceScheme` in the when clause:

```json
"menus": {
	"commandPalette": [
		{
			"command": "markdown.showSource",
			"when": "resourceScheme == markdown"
		}
	]
}
```

**Expected**
`markdown.showSource` only shows up in the command palette when you are in a markdown preview

**Actual**
`markdown.showSource` never shows up in the command palette. It seems that the `resourceScheme` context is not supported?

